13 WHEREAS, the dedication and hard work of these volunteers has significantly contributed
14 to the recovery and rebuilding of affected areas, helping to restore hope and normalcy to the
15 lives of many Georgians; and
16 WHEREAS, according to reports from local faith-based organizations, tens of thousands of
17 volunteers participated in disaster relief efforts in Georgia following Hurricane Helene,
18 contributing more than one million total volunteer hours, with teams working in some of the
19 most impacted areas to clear debris, repair homes, and provide direct assistance to many
20 thousands of affected residents; and
21 WHEREAS, many churches and faith organizations came to their fellow citizens' needs for
22 disaster relief; and
23 WHEREAS, volunteer labor from church members and faith-based organizations, who
24 traveled from as far away as South Carolina, North Carolina, Tennessee, and Florida to help
25 Georgia homeowners in need, included efforts such as tending to damaged homes, removing
26 fallen trees, and cleaning up storm debris.
27 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE that the members of this body
28 recognize and commend the invaluable contributions of the interfaith organizations and
29 volunteers in disaster cleanup efforts as well as encourage continued support and
30 collaboration among all communities to strengthen our collective ability to respond to and
31 recover from future disasters.
32 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Secretary of the Senate is authorized and directed
33 to make appropriate copies of this resolution available for distribution to the leaders of the
34 interfaith organizations involved in disaster cleanup efforts.
